Ken Stanley,



Excellent point.  The aspects of a) validating existing experimental data,
and 2) extending experimentation on priors into new realms, is messy,
humbling business.  Often, it is akin to exposing your dirty laundry to
others.  For most of us, it merely shows us how much we don&#39;t know, and the
need further work to find out.



Eventually, if we have something meaningful to contribute, hopefully we will
publish it so others can further the cause.  The problem with application of
an approach in new domains is:  You find yourself having to explain all the
inferential steps, what they mean and how they work (Yudkowsky - Expecting
Short Inferential Distances).  Strangely enough, you might be able to encode
a homology of chain complexes in something like a hyper-dimensional, CPPN to
do just that .



Ken Lloyd



From: neat@yahoogroups.com [mailto:neat@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of Ken
Sent: Friday, January 18, 2013 1:21 AM
To: neat@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [neat] Re: Open science software/experiment repository







I&#39;m all for releasing code and our group tries to do that with our own
research, but I would be hesitant about the idea of using scholarly
organizations to require people to do it. Like many well-intended rules, I
can imagine a lot of nasty unintended consequences. At a cultural level, it
would further enshrine the current benchmark obsession in machine learning
at the expense of focusing on ideas. More practically, it will mean that
reviewers will start rejecting papers based on supposed code glitches in
required code submissions. That will give reviewers a whole new
justification for completely ignoring the main of idea of the paper. 

Students will also become overwhelmed with code emergencies (since
publication will depend now upon strangers running your code) and code
cleanups demanded by random strangers who may themselves be at fault or
simply ignorant. Furthermore, in a few years we will have massive
repositories of junk code (think of the hundreds of papers published only at
GECCO in one year) that is so out of date that it requires deprecated
compilers and computing platforms even to run. But we will be required to
maintain these repositories, which will become increasingly ignored, simply
to maintain the appearance of rigor.

I&#39;d prefer just to leave it voluntary and concentrate on making it easier to
find code from people who actually want to share it and keep it up to date. 

ken


--- In neat@yahoogroups.com &lt;mailto:neat%40yahoogroups.com&gt; , Oliver Coleman
wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Yes, you make a lot of good points. It would almost certainly need support
&gt; from a publisher, or other institutions like funding bodies or
universities
&gt; to go anywhere.
&gt; 
&gt; Has anyone you know of looked into getting such organisations to require
&gt; submitting their data and code to an open repository? I&#39;m probably getting
&gt; ahead of myself here, I don&#39;t know enough about the publishers and other
&gt; organisations (except perhaps my own university) to know where to start on
&gt; such a thing... :)
&gt; 
&gt; That&#39;s a pity about Dryad only accepting CC licenses, I was planning on
&gt; using it for my next paper but my code is GPL.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; On 17 January 2013 23:32, wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; **
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Hi-
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; For those also interested in this, the previous link didn&#39;t work, it
&gt; &gt; looks
&gt; &gt; &gt; like it has an extra x at the end and should have been:
&gt; &gt; &gt; http://pages.isir.upmc.fr/evorob_db/moin.wsgi
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Oops, sorry for this. I don&#39;t know where the x is coming from.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Perhaps it would be good to create such a site (either as wiki or a
more
&gt; &gt; &gt; structured set-up) for artificial evolution research in general (with
&gt; &gt; &gt; tags/categories for sub-fields).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The main issue with a general website is that it will never be the main
&gt; &gt; reference. In my opinion, having a website with many sub-fields means
that
&gt; &gt; most people in these sub-fields will not be aware of the website, that
&gt; &gt; they will use their own solutions and, overall, that the site will be
&gt; &gt; mostly empty. As a consequence, people will not think about this website
&gt; &gt; as _the_ place to check and to submit. Put differently, I think that
such
&gt; &gt; a general website has a high probability of being a &quot;ghost website&quot;
&gt; &gt; without enough inhabitants to survive. It&#39;s &quot;easy&quot; to program a website,
&gt; &gt; it&#39;s much harder to make it alive and successful.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; That&#39;s why we tried to do something for our own, small sub-field: our
goal
&gt; &gt; is to be one of the reference pages (and even this is hard!).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The only way I can envision a successful general website is if it is
&gt; &gt; mandatory to publish a paper. For instance, GECCO could require the
&gt; &gt; submision on a specific website of the source code of every accepted
&gt; &gt; paper.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; By the way, many journals in biology now require that the authors of
&gt; &gt; accepted papers put their data (and potentially their source code) on
the
&gt; &gt; Dryad repository (http://datadryad.org/). I hope the evolutionary
&gt; &gt; computation field will be able to do the same!
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; [Dryad could be used by the EC community but it does not accept
&gt; &gt; GPL-licensed source code -- only creative commons --, whereas I think
that
&gt; &gt; many EC frameworks are distributed with a GPL-like license]
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Best regards,
&gt; &gt; -- JBM
&gt; &gt; http://people.isir.upmc.fr/mouret/
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt;
&gt;




